TRIP COMMENTS: Sacramento Audubon Society field trip led by Tim Fitzer and Mark Martucci.  Coverage was from the Salmon Falls Road up Sweetwater Creek to the end of the left spur of the trail that climbs up through chaparral. Weather was excellent; clear sky, light breeze no more than 5 mph, a cool morning start with temperatures warming to mid 70''s by noon.  It was a great morning!

TRIP COMMENTS: Howard King and I spent the morning at the San Jacinto Wildlife Area, where we did a moderately thorough search of the middle part of the refuge, as accessed mostly on foot.  Due to flooding, we did not drive into the new wetland complex.  We nevertheless walked around the most northeastern ponds of the new complex, along the San Jacinto River corridor, and around the back ponds in the northern part of the refuge.  We did not have any specific targets today, yet we had one of the best days I have ever had at the refuge, given our encountering a combination of most of the species known to be wintering here and a few new ones.  We spent as much time searching for land birds as anything else, but I did not really try to count the waterbirds carefully (though our limited coverage of the duck club ponds likely resulted in our missing many of the birds that were present).  Although numbers of waterbirds on the refuge seemed lower than they had been, huge numbers of birds on Mystic Lake suggested that many birds were still in the general area.  The deciduous trees were still mostly leafless, though some were beginning to leaf out.  It was mostly clear apart from a few high, thin clouds, initially calm but with a mild (<5 knot) breeze late in our visit, and temperatures probably increasing from the low 50s to the middle 60s (or possibly the upper 60s).  7:30-11:30 am.----Coyote - 1 (I missed one seen by Howard);--California Ground-Squirrel - 6.
SPECIES COMMENTS: (I finally saw a bird that has been present here for some time; although we identified it today as a first-winter bird, Jon Dunn later convinced me that it was probably instead a second-winter bird when we saw it again on 20 March)

This area is bounded by Kandra/Kendra Road to the north (and birds seen from here to the north edge of the circle), the Tule Lake Sump 1A dike road to the south (only including birds seen on the road or to the north), Rose Road to the east (including birds seen at the bridge over the Lost River and birds seen east to the river from the road and birds seen along the river from the dike road [south of East-West Road]), and Hill Rd to the west (excluding birds seen from Hill Rd, which is a different sector). A little bit of walking around the car in places, but most everything was car birding. Starting temp was about 14 deg F and cloudy. Cleared to sunny around 10 AM and temps up to maybe 25 deg F. Only open water was some canals that were running. Snow cover was 1-3 inches, more or less everywhere. Calm to light wind.
Includes birds seen passing through Dorris.

SPECIES COMMENTS: One bird with a clean white head and tail appeared to be an adult while a second bird (only seen perched) had a whitish head and appeared to be a second or third year bird. Body plumage on both birds otherwise brown; large yellow bill.

TRIP COMMENTS: On our way north to Santa Barbara, Brad Singer, Tom Benson, Howard King, and I made a quick detour over to Lake Casitas in search of a pair of Bald Eagles that were nesting inside the Lake Casitas Recreation Area.  The nest was located amid a stand of five or so large eucalyptus trees growing inside the park along the northern shore of the lake.  Given that we quickly located the nest and the birds, we did not spend long here, and in fact, only Brad actually entered the park, with the rest of us scanning from along Santa Ana Road.  We also did not scan the lake carefully, though we did see a few birds incidentally.  It was clear, with a mild (10+ knot) breeze from the west, and temperatures in the low 80s.  3:20-3:40 pm.
SPECIES COMMENTS: We quickly located the nest amid the large eucalyptus trees on a point just east of a cove on the north shore of the lake.  One of the birds appeared to be an adult with an entirely white head and tail and a solidly brown body, but the other bird had a whitish head with a bit of streaking and the suggestion of a dark auricular-patch, quite a bit of pale mottling on the belly and underwing coverts, and a tail that was extensively dark but with a paler base.

A survey of District 10, from Hwy 70 east on Woodruff Lane, north on Matthews; north along Ramirez; then north on Loma Rica to Quintas.  It was very windy;  there was a lot of fast traffic; pulling off was hard.  Though there were birds in many of the ponds, the largest group of 1000's was just north of Woodruff and Kimball.  There were 3 blue-morph Snow Geese at that location.  At one point, the Bald Eagle flew over and scattered the flock, but eventually they returned and the blues were nearer where I was parked.
Bruce Webb
